 Synchronous and asynchronous programming are two different approaches to handling concurrent tasks in JavaScript. 
Synchronous programming means that the execution of a function is blocked until all its dependent functions have completed executing, meaning only one function can run at a time. Here's an example of synchronous code:
```javascript
function syncExample() {
  // Code that takes some time to execute
  // This code will block until it finishes
}
```
Asynchronous programming, on the other hand, allows multiple tasks to be executed concurrently, without blocking the execution of other functions. Here's an example of asynchronous code:
```javascript
function asyncExample() {
  // Code that takes some time to execute
  // This code will run in parallel with other code
  // and not block execution
}
```
In summary, synchronous programming executes tasks sequentially, while asynchronous programming allows multiple tasks to be executed simultaneously.

